<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#555576"  width="100%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#DFDFDF" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post6657"></a>
	
	<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" ><b>Kreugen</b></font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >FoH Officer</font><br>
	<p>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Registered: Jun 2001<br>
	Location: <br>
	Posts: 148</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#DFDFDF" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b>Everquest's broken melee system (or dual wield vs the world)</b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >There is currently only one thing that I feel is broken about my character, and it does not affect merely my class alone.  And that is the fact that right now, in everquest, dual wielding dominates melee so badly that we have no choice but to dual wield.  <br>
<br>
The best two handed weapon in the game, from the boss of Temple of Veeshan Vulak'Aerr, is a 40/42 piece of junk.  Because of some flawed Law of Loot Creation at VI no weapon is allowed to have damage greater than delay.   Because of this restriction, it is impossible for anyone using a two handed weapon to do more than 2/3rds the damage of dual wield.  With the best weapons in the game, it takes three warriors using 2hs to equal two warriors dual wielding.  There are even certain one handed weapons in the game right now that do the same damage ALONE as the best two handed weapons in the game.  <br>
<br>
A good example for researching my numbers is sleepers tomb.  It is filled with 13/20 1h weapons and 33/35 2h weapons.  A warrior dual wielding the 13/20 will do at least 60% more damage than the same warrior using the two hander - and these are the ultimate weapons in the game and come from the same mobs!  Why the hell use two handers?  Aren't you sick of seeing EVERYONE dual wielding?<br>
<br>
In most game systems, dual wield is rare and difficult.  Dual wielding has no advantage over two handed weapons in raw damage, however their faster speed helps interrupt spells and the two weapons add or increase the ability to parry.   Often to make sure the two stay equal large weapons are given a high critical hit rate, such as in AD&D.   And finally, a sword and shield combination does the least damage by about 20-30% less, however the shield adds greatly to a charaters defense, especially in ranged combat (in eq, the equivalent would be giving shields an extra block ability along with dodge/parry/etc)  This is how its been in damn near any RPG system I've ever seen that has such featuers.<br>
<br>
In everquest, dual wield dominates in damage, two handers do far less damage and cannot taunt, and on the bottom you have a sword and shield combo which does far too litle damage and does not add anything significant to defense.  <br>
<br>
Why do I think this is wrong, and should be changed?  A number of reason.  First is style.  When was the last time you saw a dual wielding class in a power guild use anything OTHER than dual wield?  Wielding two weapons is difficult and uncommon.  It takes a master of dual wield to do much more than parry with his off hand.  Yet in everquest, absolutely everyone who is able to dual wield does so because it is incredibly superior to any other option in every way.  Dual wield taunts better, does more damage, allows you to have magical effects from two weapons, and now often adds as much or more AC than sword and shield combinations thanks to outrageous AC and hitpoint values placed on swords held in one hand.   The second reason is, I'm sick and tired of destroying two handed weapons that nobody wants.  There are six or so two handed weapons from ToV and NOBODY uses them.   Hell there are one handed, dual wieldable weapons from ToV that do the same damage as two handed weapons and the 1hs that are available only to pal/sk.   The third reason is aggro management.  If AC is so damned important, why is it you never see a tank actually using a shield in a battle? The reason is it is nearly impossible to hold aggro without dual wielding.  The fourth reason is of course the fact that shadowknights and paladins cannot dual wield at all, and are forced to take an additional hit to their damage on top of their offensive and weapon skill weakesses.  Paladins and shadowknights take a TRIPLE hit to their melee ability.<br>
<br>
The final reason is the most important one, however:  The gap just keeps getting bigger and bigger with every new weapon found in the game.  Two handers are limited to damage less than delay, yet one handed weapon increases exponentially every time a developer takes 1 delay off of a sword.  The gap was not nearly this wide until kunark and the Jade Mace started it all, when even VI admitted that its own desigenrs did not completly understand the way their own damage system worked and introduced 4/11 weapons superweapons to level 30 mobs.  Lack of dual wielding now puts paladins and shadowknights and anyone who would rather not wield a pair of toothpicks so far in the cellar of damage output that it's becoming a severe balance  issue.   It is much like the compaints about mana stones and cleric bp's - If you aren't dual wielding, you aren't wanted.<br>
<br>
How do I propose to fix this?  The answer is, the same way it was originally addressed back when this fact was first discovered pre-kunark, by improving the damage bonus for two handed weapons.  It is very unlikely that VI will simply upgrade or itemize two handed weapons powerful enough to approach dual wield damage - these weapons would have to be in the 60 damage 40 delay range, and I already told you about the Law of Loot Creation.  <br>
<br>
The current level 60 damage bonus for two handed weapons hovers around 20.  Double that of one handeed weapons, yes, however one handed weapons tend to be three to four times faster than two handed weapons and so their damage bonus is still technically double that of 2h.   The new forumla I propose is, for a level 60 character, the bonus on two handed weapons becomes double the base damage of the weapon.   For example, the 33/35 primal 2h axe currenlty has a minimum damge of 22, a magic number of 76, and a max hit of 197.  With the new formula, it becomes 67 minimum hit, 99 magic number, and a max of 197.  This sould raise the average damage by 40%.  It's still somewhat less than dual wield damage, but something close to this would work.<br>
<br>
The additional advantage of this formula is that weapons will scale properly - meaning the raw ratio of the weapon actually indicates it's power, wheras now you have to take into account the delay because you are adding a constant to a variable.<br>
<br>
Now, this is the MINIMUM I feel needs to be done.  It's really a drop in the ocean of the greater problem that is everquest's entire weapon system.  Here are some other suggestions along these lines:<br>
<br>
- Parry/riposte bonus for dual wielding<br>
- High critical hit rate with two handed weapons for ANY melee class.  Critial hits with one handed weapons would remain the sole ability of warriors.  The hit rate will be at least as high if not higher than common weapon procs.  Critical hits should be a common feature of two handed weapons, not a fun gimmick that goes off once every few mobs.<br>
- A higher damage bonus for one handed weapons when using a shield -  1.5x the base damage with a minimum bonus of 10.  This could possibly make it feasable to actually tank while wearing a shield, and might might it worthwile for a class other than paladin/sk to wear a shield.<br>
- An extra dodge ability while using a shield, or an increase to dodge skill.  Raw ac on the shields available in the game is simply not high enough, an extra "shield block" skill is needed to make them a viable choice.<br>
<br>
<br>
Final section: How it Should Have Been Done.   This is where I list how I would have done it in the first place.  Sort of a for-fun section or "how EQ2 should be"<br>
<br>
For starters, throw out double attack.  Increased skill in weapons translates to lowered delay and increased hit rate - all weapons will be made from the same small set of possible delays.  (ie, slow medium fast)  This is done to make life much, much easier on item makes AND it makes twinking less of an issue, because levels will have a greater impact on weapon damage.   Min/Max damage bonus is applied as a multiplyer to the base damage of a weapon and determined by a players level and/or weapon skill.  <br>
<br>
Dual wield becomes a skill path that requires hefty dedication.  Both weapons are penalized in damage and hit rate,  however only a melee dual wielding can parry.<br>
<br>
Two handed weapons will be equal to dual wield in damage, however they also get their own skill tree involving various critical attack skills that do extra damage and blow through an opponents armor for a guarranteed hit.<br>
<br>
Sword and shield combinations will add very significantly to defense, including a block ability, bashing, near immunity from ranged attacks and increased saves versus directed spells.  Damage wise the player will hit at a higher rate and for more damage than someone dual wielding, however he will do less damage overall.<br>
<br>
That is my "vision" for what a real combat system should include.  Everquest is incredbly far from it - unless you are dual wielding, your damage SUCKS and any AC inrease you get from a shield is probably not worth it.  This makes EQ's system very one dimensional and takes away choices from the players, not to mention destroys two otherwise decent classes.  <br>
<br>
I've been wanting to write this thread for some time and I've never felt up to it, so I hope this came out okay and just maybe the right person hears it.</font></p>
	
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" ><br>
